hands_on_practices.problem:
In graph theory, a "tournament" is a directed graph where for every pair of distinct vertices $\{u,v\}$, exactly one of the directed edges (arcs) $(u,v)$ or $(v,u)$ exists. This structure can model the outcomes of a round-robin tournament where every player plays every other player exactly once, and there are no draws. An arc $(u,v)$ signifies that player $u$ defeated player $v$.

A player is called a "king" if they have a path of length at most two to every other player. Formally, a vertex $k$ is a king if for every other vertex $j$ (where $j \neq k$), either the arc $(k,j)$ exists (a path of length 1), or there exists an intermediate vertex $m$ such that the arcs $(k,m)$ and $(m,j)$ both exist (a path of length 2).

Consider a tournament with four players, labeled {1, 2, 3, 4}. The outcomes of the matches are represented by the set of arcs $A = \{(1,2), (1,4), (2,3), (2,4), (3,1), (4,3)\}$.

Which of the following choices represents the complete set of kings in this tournament?

A. {2, 3}

B. {1, 2, 3, 4}

C. {4}

D. {1, 2, 3}

E. {1, 4}
